RAINFORESTS CURRENTLY
PROVIDE SOURCES FOR

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:49.000
ONE-FOURTH OF TODAY'S
MEDICINES, AND THEY ALSO

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:52.000
CONTAIN IMMENSE
UNDISCOVERED RESOURCES

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:55.000
THAT MAY HOLD THE KEY TO
UNLOCKING FUTURE CURES.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:57.000
HOWEVER, IT IS ESTIMATED
THAT NEARLY HALF OF

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:00.000
THE WORLD'S SPECIES
OF PLANTS, ANIMALS,

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:04.000
AND MICROORGANISMS WILL
BE DESTROYED OR SEVERELY

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:06.000
THREATENED OVER THE
NEXT QUARTER-CENTURY

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:09.000
DUE TO RAINFOREST
DEFORESTATION.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:11.000
WE KNOW THAT, FOR EXAMPLE,
MANY, MANY SPECIES

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:14.000
ARE BECOMING EXTINCT SO
RAPIDLY THAT WE MAY BE

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:17.000
LOOKING AT ONE OF THE
GREATEST WAVES IN THE

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:20.000
EXTINCTION OF LIFE, OR
AT LEAST MANY SPECIES

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:24.000
IN THE LAST 25, PERHAPS
50 MILLION YEARS.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:33.000
THAT'S 50,000
SPECIES A YEAR.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:36.000
ANOTHER MAJOR RESULT
OF DEFORESTATION IS IN

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
THE DISRUPTION OF
THE CARBON CYCLE.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:41.000
WITH FEWER TREES,
LESS CO2 IS ABSORBED

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:42.000
FROM THE ATMOSPHERE.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:45.000
AND, IN FACT, WHEN
THEY ARE BURNED OR ROT,

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:49.000
CARBON DIOXIDE IS RELEASED
BACK INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
THE FOCUS REALLY IS
NOW ON CLIMATE CHANGE.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:03.000
I THINK THERE'S A LOT OF
PEOPLE LOOKING AT THAT.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:07.000
GLOBAL WARMING IS WITHOUT
DOUBT THE MOST SERIOUS

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:13.000
POTENTIAL ENVIRONMENTAL
CONCERN THAT WE HAVE TODAY.

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:15.000
WE HAVE SEEN CHANGES
IN THE CLIMATE IN A

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:17.000
SHORT PERIOD OF TIME,
IN A DECADE OR SO,

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:19.000
AND IT'S SIGNIFICANT.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:22.000
IT'S THE TOPIC OF A LOT
OF RESEARCH AND IT'S

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
THE CAUSE FOR ALL THE
DEBATE AND DISCUSSION

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
ABOUT GLOBAL WARMING.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
CLIMATE CHANGE
REPRESENTS A CHANGE

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.000
IN LONG-TERM
WEATHER PATTERNS.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:34.000
THEY CAN BECOME WARMER OR
COLDER; WETTER OR DRIER.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:37.000
GLOBAL WARMING REFERS
TO AN AVERAGE INCREASE

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:39.000
IN THE EARTH'S
TEMPERATURE,

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:42.000
WHICH IN TURN CAUSES
CHANGES IN CLIMATE.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:44.000
THE EARTH'S SURFACE
TEMPERATURE HAS RISEN

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:46.000
BY ABOUT ONE
DEGREE FAHRENHEIT

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:49.000
IN THE PAST CENTURY, AND
SCIENTISTS EXPECT IT TO

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:51.000
INCREASE AN ADDITIONAL
TWO TO SIX DEGREES

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:54.000
OVER THE NEXT
HUNDRED YEARS.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:56.000
THERE'S NO DOUBT THAT THE
CLIMATE IS GETTING WARMER

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:00.000
ACROSS MUCH OF THE EARTH.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:03.000
OUR TEMPERATURE DATA
ARE PLENTY GOOD ENOUGH

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:06.000
TO DETERMINE THAT
THAT'S HAPPENING.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.000
HOWEVER, WE ALSO KNOW THAT
THE CLIMATE HAS WARMED UP

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:14.000
AND COOLED OFF A LOT IN
PREVIOUS GEOLOGICAL PERIODS.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:18.000
THE FLUCTUATIONS OF
CLIMATE ARE QUITE DRASTIC

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:22.000
AND IT'S ONLY IN THE LAST
100 MILLION YEARS OR SO

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:24.000
THAT IT'S ACTUALLY BEEN
QUITE STABLE AND THAT'S

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:27.000
PROBABLY WHY HUMANS
HAVE REALLY FLOURISHED,

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:29.000
AND LIFE IN GENERAL
HAS REALLY FLOURISHED.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:32.000
THERE ARE A NUMBER OF
DIFFERENT MECHANISMS

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:36.000
THAT WOULD ALLOW THE PLANET
TO GET WARMER AND COOLER

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:39.000
AND DIFFERENTIATING
ONE CAUSE FROM ANOTHER

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:42.000
IS EXTREMELY DIFFICULT
AND THERE'S A

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.000
VERY ACTIVE DEBATE
OVER HOW MUCH OF THAT

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:48.000
MAY BE DUE TO THE
ACTIVITIES OF PEOPLE.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.000
SCIENTISTS ARE NOT EXACTLY
SURE WHY CLIMATES CHANGE,

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:54.000
PERHAPS PERIODS OF
INCREASED HEAT FROM THE SUN

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:56.000
MAY HAVE HELPED MAKE
THE EARTH BECOME WARMER.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:59.000
BUT MANY OF THE WORLD'S
LEADING CLIMATOLOGISTS

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.000
THINK THAT HUMAN
ACTIVITIES HAVE ALTERED

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:04.000
THE CHEMICAL COMPOSITION
OF THE ATMOSPHERE

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:07.000
THROUGH THE BUILDUP
OF GREENHOUSE GASES.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:09.000
THE GREENHOUSE EFFECT
IS WHAT REGULATES

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:11.000
THE TEMPERATURE
OF OUR PLANET.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:13.000
AS THE SUN'S RAYS STRIKE
THE EARTH'S SURFACE,

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:17.000
HEAT IS RADIATED BACK
INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:20.000
SOME HEAT ESCAPES INTO
SPACE, BUT THE REMAINING

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
HEAT IS TRAPPED BY
GREENHOUSE GASES

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:27.000
SUCH AS METHANE, NITROUS
OXIDE AND CARBON DIOXIDE.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:29.000
WITHOUT A NATURAL
GREENHOUSE EFFECT,

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:32.000
THE TEMPERATURE OF THE EARTH
WOULD BE ABOUT ZERO DEGREES

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:35.000
FAHRENHEIT INSTEAD OF
ITS PRESENT 57 DEGREES.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:38.000
SO, THE CONCERN IS NOT
WITH THE FACT THAT WE HAVE

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:41.000
A GREENHOUSE EFFECT, BUT
WHETHER HUMAN ACTIVITIES

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:44.000
ARE LEADING TO AN ENHANCEMENT
OF THE GREENHOUSE EFFECT.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:46.000
INCREASED AGRICULTURE...

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:47.000
DEFORESTATION...

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:49.000
LANDFILLS...

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:50.000
INDUSTRIAL PRODUCTION...

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:53.000
AND MINING ALL CONTRIBUTE
A SIGNIFICANT AMOUNT

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:56.000
OF METHANE AND NITROUS
OXIDE, AND ESPECIALLY

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:00.000
CARBON DIOXIDE EMISSIONS
INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:03.000
MOST OF THOSE CARBON
IS LOCKED UP IN THE

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:07.000
GEOSPHERE, LIKE 80%,
AND WHAT'S HAPPENING NOW

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:10.000
IS THAT WE'RE
MESSING WITH THAT.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.000
WE'RE TAKING CARBON OUT
AS OIL AND GAS AND WE'RE

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:15.000
BURNING IT AND WE'RE PUTTING
IT INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:18.000
SO WE'RE KIND OF MESSING
WITH THE CARBON CYCLE

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:22.000
AND THAT'S WHAT'S
DRIVING GLOBAL WARMING.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.000
WELL, THE FIRST THING TO
UNDERSTAND IS HOW MUCH CO2

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:26.000
WE'RE ACTUALLY PUTTING
INTO THE ENVIRONMENT.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:30.000
SOMEWHERE BETWEEN 20
AND 50 TRILLION POUNDS

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:33.000
OF CO2 A YEAR COME OUT
OF OUR EXHAUST PIPES

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:36.000
AND OUR FACTORIES'
CHIMNEYS EVERY YEAR,

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:39.000
AND THE NUMBER IS
INCREASING EXPONENTIALLY

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:42.000
BECAUSE WE ARE CONSUMING
MORE AND MORE FOSSIL FUELS.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:45.000
THAT'S A LOT OF CO2,
AND THAT'S ENOUGH CO2,

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:49.000
WHICH IS A GREENHOUSE
GAS, TO REALLY START

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:53.000
AFFECTING THE CLIMATE
OF OUR PLANET.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:56.000
A FEW DEGREES MAY NOT
SOUND LIKE MUCH, BUT IT

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.000
COULD CHANGE THE EARTH'S
CLIMATE DRASTICALLY.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:01.000
FOR EXAMPLE, AT THE PEAK
OF THE LAST ICE AGE

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:04.000
ABOUT 18,000 YEARS AGO, THE
TEMPERATURE OF THE EARTH

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:07.000
WAS ONLY SEVEN DEGREES
FAHRENHEIT COLDER

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:09.000
THAN IT IS TODAY.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:11.000
THERE ARE MANY CONSEQUENCES
OF THIS WARMING,

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:13.000
SUCH AS HEAT WAVES
AND THE MELTING OF

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:16.000
THE POLAR ICE CAPS
AND THE GLACIERS.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.000
BY MELTING THEM, WE'RE
PUTTING MORE WATER

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:19.000
INTO THE OCEANS.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:22.000
IT'S GOING TO RAISE SEA
LEVEL, THE ANIMALS THAT

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:26.000
LIVE ON THE ICE
ARE UNDER THREAT.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:29.000
RISING SEA LEVELS CAN
RESULT IN COASTAL FLOODING

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:32.000
AND CAN EFFECT THE
LOCATION AND POPULATION

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:35.000
OF PLANT AND ANIMAL LIFE
THAT MUST ADAPT OR MOVE

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:37.000
TO SURVIVE THE
CHANGING CONDITIONS.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:40.000
GLOBAL WARMING CAN ALSO
AFFECT WEATHER PATTERNS.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.000
WITH MORE
POWERFUL STORMS,

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:44.000
INCREASED DROUGHTS
AND FIRES,

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.000
POLLUTION AND DISEASES.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.000
AND THESE ARE JUST A
FEW OF THE POTENTIAL

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:50.000
ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACTS.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:53.000
THE POTENTIAL PROBLEMS
FROM GLOBAL WARMING

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:57.000
COULD BE REALLY QUITE
CATASTROPHIC IN TERMS

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:59.000
OF CHANGING COMPLETELY
THE WEATHER PATTERNS

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:02.000
AND IF OR HOW
WE DO BUSINESS.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:05.000
SO IF YOU HAVE HURRICANES,
SERIOUS HURRICANES,

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:07.000
REPEATED HURRICANES
EVERY YEAR IN FLORIDA,

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.000
THAT CHANGES THE WAY PEOPLE
DO BUSINESS IN FLORIDA.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:13.000
MASSIVE FIRES IN THE WEST
- THAT CAUSES A LOT OF

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:17.000
MONETARY DAMAGE AS WELL AS
DAMAGE TO OUR ENVIRONMENT.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:20.000
IF A PARTICULAR REGION
IS USED TO GROWING

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:23.000
A PARTICULAR CROP AND
SUDDENLY THAT CROP...

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:26.000
IT'S TOO DRY OR TOO COLD
OR TOO HOT FOR THAT CROP

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:27.000
AND EVERYTHING
HAS TO BE CHANGED,

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:28.000
THAT'S A BIG COST.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:33.000
THESE POTENTIAL CONSEQUENCES
ARE REALLY SEVERE.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:36.000
I THINK THE BIGGEST PROBLEM
WE FACE AS A SPECIES

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
IS OVERPOPULATION.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:42.000
I THINK THAT IF WE KEEP OUR
POPULATION, OR AT LEAST

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:46.000
BE COGNIZANT OF OUR
POPULATION IN SUCH A WAY

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:49.000
THAT WE WORK IN HARMONY
WITH OUR OWN PLANET;

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:51.000
THAT WE DON'T
EXHAUST THE RESOURCES

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:54.000
THAT ARE NEEDED TO
SUSTAIN US AS A SPECIES.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.000
BUT THAT'S GOING TO BE
THE MOST IMPORTANT STEP

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:01.000
FOR OUR FUTURE
SURVIVABILITY.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:04.000
I THINK ONE OF THE THINGS
WE COULD DO TO ALLEVIATE

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:07.000
THE STRESS THAT WE PUT
ON THE ENVIRONMENT,

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:11.000
THE STRESS THAT OUR WASTE
AND OVER USE PRODUCES,

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:14.000
IS BY EDUCATING
PEOPLE A LITTLE MORE.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:18.000
I DON'T KNOW ANYONE WHO
WOULD NOT CHOOSE TO BUY

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:20.000
AN ENERGY EFFICIENT
APPLIANCE IF THEY COULD.

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:22.000
IT'S JUST THAT THEY
DON'T KNOW ANY BETTER.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:24.000
THEY DON'T REALIZE
WHAT THE DIFFERENCE IS

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:27.000
AND THEY DON'T THINK
THAT THEIR ONE SODA CAN

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:30.000
CAN AFFECT A LANDFILL.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:34.000
REDUCE, REUSE AND RECYCLE.

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:36.000
WE HAVE LEARNED THAT WE
NEED TO MAKE SACRIFICES

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:39.000
TO SAVE THE PLANET.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:40.000
THE SIMPLEST
ONE IS JUST THAT

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:43.000
THAT BIG CAR YOU'RE
DRIVING, MAYBE YOU'D

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:46.000
HAVE TO DRIVE A CAR THAT
HAS BETTER FUEL EFFICIENCY.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:49.000
WE HAVE TO BUILD OUR HOMES
WITH BETTER FUEL EFFICIENCY,

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:53.000
AND WE HAVE TO CHANGE THE
WAY WE'RE GETTING OUR ENERGY

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:56.000
FROM THE CONTINUED
USE OF FOSSIL FUELS

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:59.000
TO GETTING ENERGY FROM
RENEWABLE RESOURCES

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:01.000
SUCH AS FROM WIND POWER,
SOLAR POWER,

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:04.000
HYDROELECTRIC POWER.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:06.000
ALL OF THESE THINGS ARE
POSSIBLE AND THEY'RE

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:09.000
THINGS THAT CAN
BE DONE RIGHT NOW.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:12.000
IT IS EARTH SCIENTISTS
THAT ARE BEGINNING TO

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:14.000
RECOGNIZE SOME OF
THESE CHANGES AND WE'RE

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:16.000
BEGINNING TO TRY TO
UNDERSTAND BETTER

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:19.000
WHAT THE MAGNITUDE OF THESE
IMPACTS ARE GOING TO BE.

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:20.000
AND THAT'S WHAT'S
EXCITING, I THINK,

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:22.000
ABOUT THE EARTH SCIENCES,
THE ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCES,

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:24.000
IS WE'RE THE ONES OUT
THERE STUDYING THESE AREAS

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:26.000
AND TRYING TO FIGURE
OUT JUST EXACTLY

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:27.000
WHAT THOSE
IMPACTS WILL BE.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:29.000
IT'S NOT VERY
EASY BECAUSE

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:31.000
OFTENTIMES IT'S
VERY COMPLICATED.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:33.000
BUT WITH ENOUGH TIME,
EFFORT, AND ENERGY

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:37.000
AND ENTHUSIASM, YOU
CAN LEARN A LOT.

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:39.000
AS WE CONTINUE TO LEARN
AND DEVELOP NEW WAYS

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:42.000
TO CONSERVE, WE ALSO
LOOK TOWARD A FUTURE

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:45.000
WHEN OUR DEMANDS WILL
NOT TIP THE BALANCE

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:53.000
OF OUR DELICATE
PLANET EARTH.

